– Turkish\")\n-   [Українська](https://uk.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diff \"Diff – Ukrainian\")\n-   [中文](https://zh.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diff \"Diff – Chinese\")\n\n[Edit links](https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Special:EntityPage/Q300901#sitelinks-wikipedia \"Edit interlanguage links\")\n\n-   [Article](/wiki/Diff \"View the content page [c]\")\n-   [Talk](/wiki/Talk:Diff \"Discuss improvements to the content page [t]\")\n\n English\n\n-   [Read](/wiki/Diff)\n-   [Edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit \"Edit this page [e]\")\n-   [View history](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=history \"Past revisions of this page [h]\")\n\n Tools\n\nTools\n\nmove to sidebar hide\n\nActions\n\n-   [Read](/wiki/Diff)\n-   [Edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit \"Edit this page [e]\")\n-   [View history](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=history)\n\nGeneral\n\n-   [What links here](/wiki/Special:WhatLinksHere/Diff \"List of all English Wikipedia pages containing links to this page [j]\")\n-   [Related changes](/wiki/Special:RecentChangesLinked/Diff \"Recent changes in pages linked from this page [k]\")\n-   [Upload file](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:File_Upload_Wizard \"Upload files [u]\")\n-   [Permanent link](/w/index.php?title=Diff&oldid=1359774096 \"Permanent link to this revision of this page\")\n-   [Page information](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=info \"More information about this page\")\n-   [Cite this page](/w/index.php?title=Special:CiteThisPage&page=Diff&id=1359774096&wpFormIdentifier=titleform \"Information on how to cite this page\")\n-   [Get shortened URL](/w/index.php?title=Special:UrlShortener&url=https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FDiff)\n-   [Switch to legacy parser](/w/index.php?title=Diff&useparsoid=0)\n\nPrint/export\n\n-   [Download as PDF](/w/index.php?title=Special:DownloadAsPdf&page=Diff&action=show-download-screen \"Download this page as a PDF file\")\n-   [Printable version](/w/index.php?title=Diff&printable=yes \"Printable version of this page [p]\")\n\nIn other projects\n\n-   [Wikimedia Commons](https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Diff_\\(Software\\))\n-   [Wikidata item](https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Special:EntityPage/Q300901 \"Structured data on this page hosted by Wikidata [g]\")\n\nAppearance\n\nmove to sidebar hide\n\nFrom Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia\n\nShell command for comparing file content\n\n \n\nThis article is about the command with Unix heritage. For the general topic of file comparison, see [File comparison](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_comparison \"File comparison\"). For diffs in Wikipedia, see [Help:Diff](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Diff \"Help:Diff\"). For other uses, see [DIFF](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DIFF_\\(disambiguation\\) \"DIFF (disambiguation)\").\n\ndiff\n\n[Original authors](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programmer \"Programmer\")\n\n[Douglas McIlroy](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Douglas_McIlroy \"Douglas McIlroy\")  \n([AT&T Bell Laboratories](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AT&T_Bell_Laboratories \"AT&T Bell Laboratories\"))\n\n[Developers](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programmer \"Programmer\")\n\nVarious [open-source](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open-source_software \"Open-source software\") and [commercial](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commercial_software \"Commercial software\") developers\n\nRelease\n\nJune 1974; 52 years ago (1974-06)\n\nWritten in\n\n[C](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_\\(programming_language\\) \"C (programming language)\")\n\n[Operating system](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operating_system \"Operating system\")\n\n[Unix](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix \"Unix\"), [Unix-like](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix-like \"Unix-like\"), [V](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V_\\(operating_system\\) \"V (operating system)\"), [Plan 9](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plan_9_from_Bell_Labs \"Plan 9 from Bell Labs\"), [Inferno](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inferno_\\(operating_system\\) \"Inferno (operating system)\")\n\n[Platform](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computing_platform \"Computing platform\")\n\n[Cross-platform](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross-platform \"Cross-platform\")\n\n[Type](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_categories#Categorization_approaches \"Software categories\")\n\n[Command](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Command_\\(computing\\) \"Command (computing)\")\n\n[License](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_license \"Software license\")\n\nPlan 9: [MIT License](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MIT_License \"MIT License\")\n\n`**diff**` is a [shell](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shell_\\(computing\\) \"Shell (computing)\") [command](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Command_\\(computing\\) \"Command (computing)\") that [compares](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_comparison \"Data comparison\") the content of files and reports differences. The term *diff* is also used to identify the output of the command and is [used as a verb](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Verbed \"Verbed\") for running the command. To diff files, one runs diff to create a diff.[\\[1\\]](#cite_note-1)\n\nTypically, the command is used to compare [text files](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Text_file \"Text file\"), but it does support comparing [binary files](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_file \"Binary file\"). If one of the input files contains non-textual data, the command defaults to brief-mode, reporting only a summary indication of whether the files differ. With the `--text` option, it always reports line-based differences; however, the output may be difficult to understand, as binary data is generally not structured in lines like text.[\\[2\\]](#cite_note-2)\n\nAlthough the command is primarily used ad hoc to analyze changes between two files, a special use is for creating a [patch file](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patch_\\(computing\\) \"Patch (computing)\") for use with the `[patch](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patch_\\(Unix\\) \"Patch (Unix)\")` command – which was specifically designed to use a diff output report as a patch file. [POSIX](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/POSIX \"POSIX\") standardized the `diff` and `patch` commands including their shared file format.[\\[3\\]](#cite_note-3)\n\n## History\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit&section=1 \"Edit section: History\")\\]\n\nThe original diff [utility](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Utility_software \"Utility software\") was developed in the early 1970s for the Unix operating system, at [Bell Labs](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bell_Labs \"Bell Labs\") in Murray Hill, New Jersey. It was part of the 5th Edition of Unix released in 1974,[\\[4\\]](#cite_note-4) and was written by [Douglas McIlroy](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Douglas_McIlroy \"Douglas McIlroy\"), and [James Hunt](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_W._Hunt \"James W. Hunt\"). This research was published in a 1976 paper co-written with James W. Hunt, who developed an initial prototype of diff.[\\[5\\]](#cite_note-diff_paper-5) The algorithm this paper described became known as the [Hunt–Szymanski algorithm](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hunt–Szymanski_algorithm \"Hunt–Szymanski algorithm\").\n\nMcIlroy's work was preceded and influenced by [Steve Johnson](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_C._Johnson \"Stephen C. Johnson\")'s comparison program on [GECOS](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GECOS \"GECOS\") and [Mike Lesk](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Lesk \"Mike Lesk\")'s proof program. Proof also originated on Unix and, like diff, produced line-by-line changes and even used angle-brackets (\">\" and \"<\") to indicate line insertions and deletions in the program's output. The [heuristics](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heuristic \"Heuristic\") used in these early applications were, however, deemed unreliable. The potential usefulness of a diff tool led McIlroy to research and design a more robust tool for a variety of tasks that could perform well under the processing and size limitations of the [PDP-11](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PDP-11 \"PDP-11\")'s hardware. His approach to the problem resulted from collaboration with individuals at Bell Labs, including [Alfred Aho](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Aho \"Alfred Aho\"), Elliot Pinson, [Jeffrey Ullman](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeffrey_Ullman \"Jeffrey Ullman\"), and Harold S. Stone.\n\nIn the context of Unix, the use of the [ed](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ed_\\(Unix\\) \"Ed (Unix)\") line editor provided diff with the natural ability to create machine-usable \"edit scripts\". These edit scripts, when saved to a file, can, along with the original file, be reconstituted by ed into the modified file in its entirety. This greatly reduced the [secondary storage](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secondary_storage \"Secondary storage\") necessary to maintain multiple versions of a file. McIlroy considered writing a post-processor for diff where a variety of output formats could be designed and implemented; however, he found it more frugal and simpler to have diff be responsible for generating the syntax and reverse-order input accepted by the ed command.\n\nIn 1984, [Larry Wall](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Larry_Wall \"Larry Wall\") created the [patch](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patch_\\(Unix\\) \"Patch (Unix)\") utility (releasing its source code on the *mod.sources* and *net.sources* newsgroups[\\[6\\]](#cite_note-6)[\\[7\\]](#cite_note-7)[\\[8\\]](#cite_note-8)) for patching text files, using the output from diff plus the diff input file with the content before changes to create a file with the content after changes.\n\n[X/Open](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X/Open \"X/Open\") Portability Guide issue 2 of 1987 includes diff. Context mode was added in POSIX.1-2001 (issue 6). Unified mode was added in POSIX.1-2008 (issue 7).[\\[9\\]](#cite_note-9)\n\nIn diff's early years, common uses included comparing changes in software source code and markup for technical documents, verifying program debugging output, comparing filesystem listings, and analyzing computer assembly code. The output targeted for ed was motivated to provide compression for a sequence of modifications made to a file.[\\[10\\]](#cite_note-10)\\[*[citation needed](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed \"Wikipedia:Citation needed\")*\\] The [Source Code Control System](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Source_Code_Control_System \"Source Code Control System\") (SCCS) and its ability to archive revisions emerged in the late 1970s as a consequence of storing edit scripts from diff.\\[*[citation needed](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed \"Wikipedia:Citation needed\")*\\]\n\n## Algorithm\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit&section=2 \"Edit section: Algorithm\")\\]\n\nUnlike [edit distance](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edit_distance \"Edit distance\") notions used for other purposes, `diff` is line-oriented rather than character-oriented, but it is like [Levenshtein distance](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levenshtein_distance \"Levenshtein distance\") in that it tries to determine the smallest set of deletions and insertions to create one file from the other.\n\nThe operation of diff is based on solving the [longest common subsequence problem](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Longest_common_subsequence_problem \"Longest common subsequence problem\").[\\[5\\]](#cite_note-diff_paper-5) In this problem, given two sequences of items:\n\na b c d f g h j q z\n\na b c d e f g i j k r x y z\n\nand we want to find the longest sequence of items that is present in both original sequences in the same order. That is, we want to find a new sequence that can be obtained from the first original sequence by deleting some items and from the second original sequence by deleting other items. We also want this sequence to be as long as possible. In this case, it is\n\na b c d  f  g  j  z\n\nFrom a longest common subsequence, it is only a small step to get diff\\-like output: if an item is absent in the subsequence but present in the first original sequence, it must have been deleted (as indicated by the '-' marks, below). If it is absent in the subsequence but present in the second original sequence, it must have been inserted (as indicated by the '+' marks).\n\ne   h i   q   k r x y\n+   - +   -   + + + +\n\n## Use\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit&section=3 \"Edit section: Use\")\\]\n\nThe `diff` command accepts two arguments like: `diff *original* *new*`. Commonly, the arguments each identify normal files; however, if the two arguments identify directories, then the command compares corresponding files in the directories. With the `-r` option, it recursively descends matching subdirectories to compare files with corresponding relative paths.\n\n### Default output format\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit&section=4 \"Edit section: Default output format\")\\]\n\nThe example below shows the original and new file content as well as the resulting `diff` output in the default format. The output is shown with coloring to improve readability. GNU diff can colorize output when the `--color` option is used; when no `--color` option is specified, color output is disabled by default.[\\[11\\]](#cite_note-11)\n\n*original*:\n\nThis part of the\ndocument has stayed the\nsame from version to\nversion. It shouldn't\nbe shown if it doesn't\nchange. Otherwise, that\nwould not be helping to\ncompress the size of the\nchanges.\nThis paragraph contains\ntext that is outdated.\nIt will be deleted in the\nnear future.\nIt is important to spell\ncheck this dokument. On\nthe other hand, a\nmisspelled word isn't\nthe end of the world.\nNothing in the rest of\nthis paragraph needs to\nbe changed. Things can\nbe added after it.\n\n*new*:\n\nThis is an important\nnotice! It should\ntherefore be located at\nthe beginning of this\ndocument!\nThis part of the\ndocument has stayed the\nsame from version to\nversion. It shouldn't\nbe shown if it doesn't\nchange. Otherwise, that\nwould not be helping to\ncompress the size of the\nchanges.\nIt is important to spell\ncheck this document. On\nthe other hand, a\nmisspelled word isn't\nthe end of the world.\nNothing in the rest of\nthis paragraph needs to\nbe changed. Things can\nbe added after it.\nThis paragraph contains\nimportant new additions\nto this document.\n\noutput:\n\n0a1,6\n\\> This is an important\n> notice! It should\n> therefore be located at\n> the beginning of this\n> document!\n>\n11,15d16\n< This paragraph contains\n< text that is outdated.\n< It will be deleted in the\n< near future.\n<\n17c18\n< check this dokument. On\n---\n\\> check this document. On\n24a26,29\n\\>\n> This paragraph contains\n> important new additions\n> to this document.\n\nIn this default format, `a` indicates added, `d` indicates deleted, and `c` indicates changed. The line number of the original file appears before the single-letter code, and the line number of the new file appears after. The [less-than](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Less-than_sign \"Less-than sign\") and [greater-than](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greater-than_sign \"Greater-than sign\") signs (at the beginning of lines that are added, deleted, or changed) indicate which file the lines appear in. Addition lines are added to the original file and appear in the new file. Deletion lines are deleted from the original file and are missing in the new file.\n\nBy default, lines common to both files are not shown. Lines that have moved are shown as added at their new location and as deleted from their old location.[\\[12\\]](#cite_note-12) However, some diff tools highlight moved lines.\n\n### Edit script\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit&section=5 \"Edit section: Edit script\")\\]\n\nAn [ed](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ed_\\(text_editor\\) \"Ed (text editor)\") script can be generated by modern versions of diff with the `-e` option. The resulting edit script for this example is as follows:\n\n24**a**\n\n*This paragraph contains*\n*important new additions*\n*to this document.*\n.\n17**c**\n*check this document. On*\n.\n11,15**d**\n0**a**\n*This is an important*\n*notice! It should*\n*therefore be located at*\n*the beginning of this*\n*document!*\n\n.\n\nTo transform the content of the original file into the content of new file using ed, one appends two lines to this diff file, one line containing a `w` (write) command, and one containing a `q` (quit) command (e.g. by `printf \"w\\nq\\n\" >> mydiff`). Here we give the diff file the name *mydiff* and the transformation will happen when we run `ed -s original < mydiff`.\n\n### Context format\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit&section=6 \"Edit section: Context format\")\\]\n\nThe [Berkeley distribution of Unix](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BSD \"BSD\") made a point of adding the *context format* (`-c`) and the ability to recurse on filesystem directory structures (`-r`), adding those features in 2.8 BSD, released in July 1981. The context format of diff introduced at Berkeley helped distribute patches for source code that may have been changed minimally.\n\nIn the context format, any changed lines are shown alongside unchanged lines before and after. The inclusion of any number of unchanged lines provides *context* for the patch. The *context* consists of lines that have not changed between the two files and is a reference to locate the lines' in the modified file and find the intended location for a change to be applied, regardless of whether the line numbers still correspond. The context format improves readability for humans and reliability when applying the patch, and an output that is accepted as input to the [patch](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patch_\\(Unix\\) \"Patch (Unix)\") program. This intelligent behavior is not possible with the traditional diff output.\n\nThe number of unchanged lines shown above and below a change *hunk* can be defined by the user, even zero, but three lines is typically the default. If the context of unchanged lines in a hunk overlaps with an adjacent hunk, then diff will avoid duplicating the unchanged lines and merge the hunks into a single hunk.\n\nA \"`!`\" represents a change between lines that correspond in the two files, whereas a \"`+`\" represents the addition of a line, and a \"`-`\" the removal of a line. A blank [space](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space_\\(punctuation\\) \"Space (punctuation)\") represents an unchanged line. At the beginning of the patch is the file information, including the full path and a [time stamp](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_stamp \"Time stamp\") delimited by a tab character. At the beginning of each hunk are the line numbers that apply to the corresponding change in the files. A number range appearing between sets of three asterisks applies to the original file; sets of three dashes apply to the new file. The hunk ranges specify the starting and ending line numbers in the respective file.\n\nThe command `diff -c original new` produces the following output:\n\n\\*\\*\\* /path/to/original\ttimestamp\n\\--- /path/to/new\ttimestamp\n\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\n\\*\\*\\* 1,3 \\*\\*\\*\\*\n\\--- 1,9 ----\n\\+ This is an important\n\\+ notice! It should\n\\+ therefore be located at\n\\+ the beginning of this\n\\+ document!\n+\n  This part of the\n  document has stayed the\n  same from version to\n\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\n\\*\\*\\* 8,20 \\*\\*\\*\\*\n  compress the size of the\n  changes.\n\n\\- This paragraph contains\n\\- text that is outdated.\n\\- It will be deleted in the\n\\- near future.\n\n  It is important to spell\n! check this dokument. On\n  the other hand, a\n  misspelled word isn't\n  the end of the world.\n\\--- 14,21 ----\n  compress the size of the\n  changes.\n\n  It is important to spell\n! check this document. On\n  the other hand, a\n  misspelled word isn't\n  the end of the world.\n\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\n\\*\\*\\* 22,24 \\*\\*\\*\\*\n\\--- 23,29 ----\n  this paragraph needs to\n  be changed. Things can\n  be added after it.\n+\n\\+ This paragraph contains\n\\+ important new additions\n\\+ to this document.\n\n### Unified format\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit&section=7 \"Edit section: Unified format\")\\]\n\nThe *unified format* (or *unidiff*)[\\[13\\]](#cite_note-13)[\\[14\\]](#cite_note-14) inherits the technical improvements made by the context format, but produces a smaller diff with old and new text presented immediately adjacent. Unified format is usually invoked using the \"`-u`\" [command-line option](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Command-line_option \"Command-line option\"). This output is often used as input to the [patch](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patch_\\(Unix\\) \"Patch (Unix)\") program. Many projects specifically request that \"diffs\" be submitted in the unified format, making unified diff format the most common format for exchange between software developers.\n\nUnified context diffs were originally developed by Wayne Davison in August 1990 (in **unidiff** which appeared in Volume 14 of comp.sources.misc). [Richard Stallman](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Stallman \"Richard Stallman\") added unified diff support to the [GNU Project](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GNU \"GNU\")'s diff one month later. The feature debuted in **GNU diff** 1.15, released in January 1991. GNU diff has since generalized the context format to allow arbitrary formatting of diffs.\n\nThe format starts with the same two-line [header](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Header_\\(computing\\) \"Header (computing)\") as the context format, except that the original file is preceded by \"\\---\" and the new file is preceded by \"+++\". Following this are one or more **change hunks** that contain the line differences in the file. A space character precedes the unchanged, contextual lines, a [plus sign](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plus_sign \"Plus sign\") precedes addition lines, and a [minus sign](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minus_sign \"Minus sign\") precedes deletion lines.\n\nA hunk begins with **range information**; it immediately precedes the line additions, line deletions, and any number of contextual lines. The range information is surrounded by double [at signs](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/At_sign \"At sign\") and combines onto one line what appears on two lines in the context format ([above](#Context_format)). The format of the range information line is as follows:\n\n@@ -l,s +l,s @@ *optional section heading*\n\nThe hunk range information contains two hunk ranges. A minus symbol precedes the range for the hunk of the original file, and a plus symbol precedes the range for the new file. Each hunk range is of the format *l,s* where *l* is the starting line number and *s* is the number of lines the change hunk applies to for each respective file. In many versions of GNU diff, each range can omit the comma and trailing value *s*, in which case *s* defaults to 1. Note that the only really interesting value is the *l* line number of the first range; all the other values can be computed from the diff.\n\nThe hunk range for the original should be the sum of all contextual and deletion (including changed) hunk lines. The hunk range for the new file should be a sum of all contextual and addition (including changed) hunk lines. If hunk size information does not correspond with the number of lines in the hunk, then the diff could be considered invalid and rejected.\n\nOptionally, the hunk range can be followed by the heading of the section or function that the hunk is part of. This is mainly useful to make the diff easier to read. When creating a diff with GNU diff, the heading is identified by [regular expression](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_expression \"Regular expression\") matching.[\\[15\\]](#cite_note-15)\n\nIf a line is modified, it is represented as a deletion and addition. Since the hunks of the original and new file appear in the same hunk, such changes would appear adjacent to one another.[\\[16\\]](#cite_note-16) An occurrence of this in the example below is:\n\n\\-check this dokument. On\n+check this document. On\n\nThe command `diff -u original new` produces the following output:\n\n\\--- /path/to/original\ttimestamp\n+++ /path/to/new\ttimestamp\n@@ -1,3 +1,9 @@\n+This is an important\n+notice! It should\n+therefore be located at\n+the beginning of this\n+document!\n+\n This part of the\n document has stayed the\n same from version to\n@@ -8,13 +14,8 @@\n compress the size of the\n changes.\n\n\\-This paragraph contains\n\\-text that is outdated.\n\\-It will be deleted in the\n\\-near future.\n\\-\n It is important to spell\n\\-check this dokument. On\n+check this document. On\n the other hand, a\n misspelled word isn't\n the end of the world.\n@@ -22,3 +23,7 @@\n this paragraph needs to\n be changed. Things can\n be added after it.\n+\n+This paragraph contains\n+important new additions\n+to this document.\n\nTo successfully separate the file names from the timestamps, a tab character serves as the delimiter. This is invisible on screen and can be lost when diffs are copied and pasted from console/terminal screens.\n\n### Extensions\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit&section=8 \"Edit section: Extensions\")\\]\n\nThere are some modifications and extensions to the diff formats that are used and understood by certain programs and in certain contexts. For example, some [revision control](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revision_control \"Revision control\") systems—such as [Subversion](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subversion_\\(software\\) \"Subversion (software)\")—specify a version number, \"working copy\", or any other comment instead of or in addition to a timestamp in the diff's header section.\n\nSome tools allow diffs for several different files to be merged into one, using a header for each modified file that may look something like this:\n\nIndex: path/to/file.cpp\n\nThe special case of files that do not end in a newline is not handled. Neither `unidiff` nor the POSIX `diff` standard defines a way to handle this type of file. (Indeed, such files are not \"text\" files by strict POSIX definitions.[\\[17\\]](#cite_note-17)) GNU diff and git produce \"\\\\ No newline at end of file\" (or a translated version) as a diagnostic, but this behavior is not portable.[\\[18\\]](#cite_note-18) GNU patch does not seem to handle this case, while git-apply does.[\\[19\\]](#cite_note-19)\n\nThe [patch](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patch_\\(Unix\\) \"Patch (Unix)\") program does not necessarily recognize implementation-specific diff output. However, GNU patch recognizes git patches and will act a little differently.[\\[20\\]](#cite_note-20)\n\n## Implementations and related programs\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit&section=9 \"Edit section: Implementations and related programs\")\\]\n\nChanges since 1975 include improvements to the core algorithm, the addition of useful features to the command, and the design of new output formats. The basic algorithm is described in the papers *An O(ND) Difference Algorithm and its Variations* by [Eugene W. Myers](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugene_Myers \"Eugene Myers\")[\\[21\\]](#cite_note-21) and in *A File Comparison Program* by Webb Miller and Myers.[\\[22\\]](#cite_note-22) The algorithm was independently discovered and described in *Algorithms for Approximate String Matching*, by [Esko Ukkonen](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esko_Ukkonen \"Esko Ukkonen\").[\\[23\\]](#cite_note-23) The first editions of the diff program were designed for line comparisons of text files, expecting the [newline](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newline \"Newline\") character to delimit lines. By the 1980s, support for binary files shifted the application's design and implementation.\n\nGNU diff and diff3 are included in the **diffutils** package with other diff and [patch](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patch_\\(Unix\\) \"Patch (Unix)\") related utilities.[\\[24\\]](#cite_note-24)\n\n### Formatters and front-ends\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit&section=10 \"Edit section: Formatters and front-ends\")\\]\n\nPostprocessors **sdiff** and **diffmk** render side-by-side diff listings and applied change marks to printed documents, respectively. Both were developed elsewhere in Bell Labs in or before 1981.\\[*[citation needed](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed \"Wikipedia:Citation needed\")*\\]\\[*[discuss](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:Diff#topicality_of_front-ends \"Talk:Diff\")*\\]\n\n[Diff3](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diff3 \"Diff3\") compares one file against two other files by reconciling two diffs. It was originally conceived by Paul Jensen to reconcile changes made by two people editing a common source. It is also used by revision control systems, e.g. [RCS](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revision_Control_System \"Revision Control System\"), for [merging](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merge_\\(revision_control\\) \"Merge (revision control)\").[\\[25\\]](#cite_note-25)\n\n[Emacs](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emacs \"Emacs\") has [Ediff](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ediff \"Ediff\"), which shows the changes a patch would provide in a user interface that combines interactive editing and merging capabilities for patch files.\n\n[Vim](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vim_\\(text_editor\\) \"Vim (text editor)\") provides **vimdiff** to compare from two to eight files, with differences highlighted in color.[\\[26\\]](#cite_note-26) While historically invoking the diff program, modern vim uses [git](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Git \"Git\")'s fork of xdiff library (LibXDiff) code, providing improved speed and functionality.[\\[27\\]](#cite_note-brabandt2018-27)\n\nGNU [Wdiff](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wdiff?action=edit&redlink=1 \"Wdiff (page does not exist)\")[\\[28\\]](#cite_note-28) is a front end to diff that shows the words or phrases that changed in a text document of written language even in the presence of word-wrapping or different column widths.\n\ncolordiff is a Perl wrapper for 'diff' that produces the same output, but with colorization for added and deleted bits.[\\[29\\]](#cite_note-29) diff-so-fancy and diff-highlight are newer analogues.[\\[30\\]](#cite_note-30) \"delta\" is a Rust rewrite that highlights changes and the underlying code at the same time.[\\[31\\]](#cite_note-31)\n\n**Patchutils** contains tools that combine, rearrange, compare, and fix context diffs and unified diffs.[\\[32\\]](#cite_note-32)\n\n### Algorithmic derivatives\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit&section=11 \"Edit section: Algorithmic derivatives\")\\]\n\nUtilities that compare source files by their syntactic structure have been built mostly as research tools for some programming languages;[\\[33\\]](#cite_note-33)[\\[34\\]](#cite_note-34)[\\[35\\]](#cite_note-35) some are available as commercial tools.[\\[36\\]](#cite_note-36)[\\[37\\]](#cite_note-37) In addition, free tools that perform syntax-aware diff include:\n\n-   C++: zograscope, AST-based.[\\[38\\]](#cite_note-38)\n-   HTML: Daisydiff,[\\[39\\]](#cite_note-39) html-differ.\n-   XML: *xmldiffpatch* by Microsoft and *xmldiffmerge* for IBM.[\\[40\\]](#cite_note-40)[\\[41\\]](#cite_note-41)\n-   [JavaScript](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaScript \"JavaScript\"): astii (AST-based).\n-   Multi-language: [Pretty Diff](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pretty_Diff \"Pretty Diff\") (format code and then diff)[\\[42\\]](#cite_note-42)\n\n**spiff** is a variant of *diff* that ignores differences in floating point calculations with roundoff errors and [whitespace](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space_\\(punctuation\\) \"Space (punctuation)\"), both of which are generally irrelevant to source code comparison. [Bellcore](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telcordia_Technologies \"Telcordia Technologies\") wrote the original version.[\\[43\\]](#cite_note-dontcallme-43)[\\[44\\]](#cite_note-hpux-44) An [HPUX](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HPUX \"HPUX\") port is the most current public release. spiff does not support binary files. spiff outputs to the [standard output](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_output \"Standard output\") in standard diff format and accepts inputs in the [C](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_\\(programming_language\\) \"C (programming language)\"), [Bourne shell](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bourne_shell \"Bourne shell\"), [Fortran](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fortran \"Fortran\"), [Modula-2](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modula-2 \"Modula-2\") and [Lisp](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lisp_\\(programming_language\\) \"Lisp (programming language)\") [programming languages](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language \"Programming language\").[\\[45\\]](#cite_note-45)[\\[46\\]](#cite_note-46)[\\[43\\]](#cite_note-dontcallme-43)[\\[47\\]](#cite_note-47)[\\[44\\]](#cite_note-hpux-44)\n\nLibXDiff is an LGPL [library](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Library_\\(computing\\) \"Library (computing)\") that provides an interface to many algorithms from 1998. An improved Myers algorithm with [Rabin fingerprint](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rabin_fingerprint \"Rabin fingerprint\") was originally implemented (as of the final release of 2008),[\\[48\\]](#cite_note-48) but [git](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Git \"Git\") and [libgit2](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Libgit2 \"Libgit2\")'s fork has since expanded the repository with many of its own. One algorithm called \"histogram\" is generally regarded as better than the original Myers algorithm, both in speed and quality.[\\[49\\]](#cite_note-49)[\\[50\\]](#cite_note-50) This is the modern version of *LibXDiff* used by Vim.[\\[27\\]](#cite_note-brabandt2018-27)\n\n## See also\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit&section=12 \"Edit section: See also\")\\]\n\n-   [cmp](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cmp_\\(Unix\\) \"Cmp (Unix)\") – File comparison command\n-   [Comparison of file comparison tools](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_file_comparison_tools \"Comparison of file comparison tools\")\n-   [Delta encoding](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delta_encoding \"Delta encoding\") – Type of data transmission method\n-   [Difference operator](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Difference_operator \"Difference operator\") – Pattern defining an infinite sequence of numbersPages displaying short descriptions of redirect targets\n-   [File Compare](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_Compare \"File Compare\") – Command-line program that compares multiple files\n-   [History of software configuration management](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_software_configuration_management \"History of software configuration management\")\n-   [Revision control](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revision_control \"Revision control\") – Managing versions of source code or dataPages displaying short descriptions of redirect targets\n-   [Software configuration management](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_configuration_management \"Software configuration management\") – Tracking and controlling software changes\n-   [WinDiff](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WinDiff \"WinDiff\") – File comparison program by Microsoft\n-   [Ramseyer Rule](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramseyer_Rule \"Ramseyer Rule\") - standard format for amending legal text\n\n## References\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Diff&action=edit&section=13 \"Edit section: References\")\\]\n\n1.  [↑](#cite_ref-1) Eric S. Raymond (ed.), [\"diff\"](http://catb.org/jargon/html/D/diff.html) [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20140131071625/http://www.catb.org/jargon/html/D/diff.html) 2014-01-31 at the [Wayback Machine](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wayback_Machine \"Wayback Machine\"), *The Jargon File*, version 4.4.7\n2.  [↑](#cite_ref-2) MacKenzie *et al.* \"Binary Files and Forcing Text Comparison\" in *Comparing and Merging Files with GNU Diff and Patch*. Downloaded 28 April 2007. [](https://www.gnu.org/software/diffutils/manual/html_node/Binary.html)[Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20171219223414/http://www.gnu.org/software/diffutils/manual/html_node/Binary.html) 2017-12-19 at the [Wayback Machine](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wayback_Machine \"Wayback Machine\")\n3.  [↑](#cite_ref-3) [IEEE Computer Society](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_Computer_Society \"IEEE Computer Society\"); [The Open Group](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Open_Group \"The Open Group\") (26 September 2008). *Standard for Information Technology—Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) Base Specifications, Issue 7*. pp. 2599–2607. IEEE Std. 1003.1-2001 specifies traditional, \"ed script\", and context diff output formats; IEEE Std. 1003.1-2008 added the (by then more common) unified format.\n4.  [↑](#cite_ref-4) [\"diff - differential file comparison\"](https://minnie.tuhs.org/cgi-bin/utree.pl?file=V5/usr/source/s1/diff1.c). *minnie.tuhs.org*. Retrieved 2026-03-25.\n5.  [1](#cite_ref-diff_paper_5-0) [2](#cite_ref-diff_paper_5-1) James W. Hunt; M. Douglas McIlroy (June 1976). [\"An Algorithm for Differential File Comparison\"](http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/~doug/diff.pdf) (PDF). *Computing Science Technical Report, Bell Laboratories*. **41**. [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20141226005228/http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/~doug/diff.pdf) (PDF) from the original on 2014-12-26. Retrieved 2015-05-06.\n6.  [↑](#cite_ref-6) Larry Wall (November 9, 1984). [\"A patch applier--YOU WANT THIS!!!\"](https://groups.google.com/d/msg/net.sources/qtfVio1sSHs/G0cPT5HFDFcJ). [Newsgroup](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Usenet_newsgroup \"Usenet newsgroup\"): [net.sources](news:net.sources). [Usenet:](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Usenet_\\(identifier\\) \"Usenet (identifier)\") [1457@sdcrdcf.UUCP](news:1457@sdcrdcf.UUCP). [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20220219233604/https://groups.google.com/g/net.sources/c/qtfVio1sSHs/m/G0cPT5HFDFcJ) from the original on February 19, 2022. Retrieved May 11, 2015.\n7.  [↑](#cite_ref-7) Larry Wall (November 29, 1984). [\"patch version 1.2--YOU WANT THIS\"](https://groups.google.com/d/msg/net.sources/uWFr9NOp_fw/SRS_P2vSgFgJ). [Newsgroup](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Usenet_newsgroup \"Usenet newsgroup\"): [net.sources](news:net.sources). [Usenet:](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Usenet_\\(identifier\\) \"Usenet (identifier)\") [1508@sdcrdcf.UUCP](news:1508@sdcrdcf.UUCP). [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20200321140052/https://groups.google.com/forum/) from the original on March 21, 2020. Retrieved May 11, 2015.\n8.  [↑](#cite_ref-8) Larry Wall (May 8, 1985). [\"patch version 1.3\"](https://groups.google.com/d/msg/mod.sources/xSQM63e39YY/apNNJSkJi0gJ). [Newsgroup](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Usenet_newsgroup \"Usenet newsgroup\"): [net.sources](news:net.sources). [Usenet:](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Usenet_\\(identifier\\) \"Usenet (identifier)\") [813@genrad.UUCP](news:813@genrad.UUCP). [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20220219233604/https://groups.google.com/g/mod.sources/c/xSQM63e39YY/m/apNNJSkJi0gJ) from the original on February 19, 2022. Retrieved May 11, 2015.\n9.  [↑](#cite_ref-9) `[diff](https://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/9799919799/utilities/diff.html)` – Shell and Utilities Reference, [The Single UNIX Specification](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single_Unix_Specification \"Single Unix Specification\"), Version 5 from [The Open Group](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Open_Group \"The Open Group\")\n10.  [↑](#cite_ref-10) Ritchie, Dennis M.; Thompson, Ken (1974-07-01). [\"The UNIX time-sharing system\"](https://doi.org/10.1145/361011.361061). *Commun. ACM*. **17** (7): 365–375\\. [doi](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doi_\\(identifier\\) \"Doi (identifier)\"):[10.1145/361011.361061](https://doi.org/10.1145%2F361011.361061). [ISSN](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISSN_\\(identifier\\) \"ISSN (identifier)\") [0001-0782](https://search.worldcat.org/issn/0001-0782).\n11.  [↑](#cite_ref-11) [\"diff Options\"](https://www.gnu.org/software/diffutils/manual/html_node/diff-Options.html). *GNU Diffutils Manual*. Free Software Foundation. Retrieved 11 June 2026.\n12.  [↑](#cite_ref-12) David MacKenzie; Paul Eggert; Richard Stallman (1997). [*Comparing and Merging Files with GNU Diff and Patch*](https://www.gnu.org/software/diffutils/manual/). Bristol: Network Theory. [ISBN](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_\\(identifier\\) \"ISBN (identifier)\") [978-0-9541617-5-0](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-9541617-5-0 \"Special:BookSources/978-0-9541617-5-0\"). [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20150331031946/http://www.gnu.org/software/diffutils/manual/) from the original on 2015-03-31. Retrieved 2015-03-17.\n13.  [↑](#cite_ref-13) [\"Detailed Description of Unified Format\"](https://www.gnu.org/software/diffutils/manual/html_node/Detailed-Unified.html). *GNU Diffutils (version 3.7, 7 January 2018)*. [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20200118142136/http://www.gnu.org/software/diffutils/manual/html_node/Detailed-Unified.html) from the original on 18 January 2020. Retrieved 29 January 2020.\n14.  [↑](#cite_ref-14) van Rossum, Guido. [\"Unified Diff Format\"](https://www.artima.com/weblogs/viewpost.jsp?thread=164293). *All Things Pythonic*. [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20191225234517/https://www.artima.com/weblogs/viewpost.jsp?thread=164293) from the original on 2019-12-25. Retrieved 2020-01-29.\n15.  [↑](#cite_ref-15) [2.2.3 Showing Which Sections Differences Are in](https://www.gnu.org/software/diffutils/manual/html_node/Sections.html), GNU diffutils manual\n16.  [↑](#cite_ref-16) [Unified Diff Format](http://www.artima.com/weblogs/viewpost.jsp?thread=164293) by [Guido van Rossum](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guido_van_Rossum \"Guido van Rossum\"), June 14, 2006\n17.  [↑](#cite_ref-17) [http://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/9699919799/basedefs/V1\\_chap03.html#tag\\_03\\_403](http://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/9699919799/basedefs/V1_chap03.html#tag_03_403) [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20130429195728/http://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/9699919799/basedefs/V1_chap03.html#tag_03_403) 2013-04-29 at the [Wayback Machine](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wayback_Machine \"Wayback Machine\") Section 3.206\n18.  [↑](#cite_ref-18) [\"Incomplete Lines (Comparing and Merging Files)\"](https://www.gnu.org/software/diffutils/manual/html_node/Incomplete-Lines.html). *www.gnu.org*. [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20230508092618/https://www.gnu.org/software/diffutils/manual/html_node/Incomplete-Lines.html) from the original on 2023-05-08. Retrieved 2023-06-15.\n19.  [↑](#cite_ref-19) [\"git: apply.c\"](https://github.com/git/git/blob/69c786637d7a7fe3b2b8f7d989af095f5f49c3a8/apply.c#LL2901C35-L2901C39). Git. 8 May 2023. [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20230513063349/https://github.com/git/git/blob/69c786637d7a7fe3b2b8f7d989af095f5f49c3a8/apply.c#LL2901C35-L2901C39) from the original on 13 May 2023. Retrieved 15 June 2023.\n20.  [↑](#cite_ref-20) [\"patch.c\\\\src - patch.git - GNU patch\"](https://git.savannah.gnu.org/cgit/patch.git/tree/src/patch.c?id=c835ecc67b7e37c0d0b7dd7e032209fdaa285808#n1919). *git.savannah.gnu.org*. [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20230508094116/https://git.savannah.gnu.org/cgit/patch.git/tree/src/patch.c?id=c835ecc67b7e37c0d0b7dd7e032209fdaa285808#n1919) from the original on 2023-05-08. Retrieved 2023-06-15. In git-style diffs, the \"before\" state of each patch refers to the initial state before modifying any files,..\n21.  [↑](#cite_ref-21) E. Myers (1986). \"An O(ND) Difference Algorithm and Its Variations\". *Algorithmica*. **1** (2): 251–266\\. [CiteSeerX](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CiteSeerX_\\(identifier\\) \"CiteSeerX (identifier)\") [10.1.1.4.6927](https://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/summary?doi=10.1.1.4.6927). [doi](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doi_\\(identifier\\) \"Doi (identifier)\"):[10.1007/BF01840446](https://doi.org/10.1007%2FBF01840446). [S2CID](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S2CID_\\(identifier\\) \"S2CID (identifier)\") [6996809](https://api.semanticscholar.org/CorpusID:6996809).\n22.  [↑](#cite_ref-22) Webb Miller; Eugene W. Myers (1985). \"A File Comparison Program\". *Software: Practice and Experience*. **15** (11): 1025–1040\\. [CiteSeerX](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CiteSeerX_\\(identifier\\) \"CiteSeerX (identifier)\") [10.1.1.189.70](https://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/summary?doi=10.1.1.189.70). [doi](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doi_\\(identifier\\) \"Doi (identifier)\"):[10.1002/spe.4380151102](https://doi.org/10.1002%2Fspe.4380151102). [S2CID](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S2CID_\\(identifier\\) \"S2CID (identifier)\") [15489614](https://api.semanticscholar.org/CorpusID:15489614).\n23.  [↑](#cite_ref-23) Esko Ukkonen (1985). [\"Algorithms for Approximate String Matching\"](https://doi.org/10.1016%2FS0019-9958%2885%2980046-2). *Information and Control*. **64** (1–3): 100–118\\. [doi](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doi_\\(identifier\\) \"Doi (identifier)\"):[10.1016/S0019-9958(85)80046-2](https://doi.org/10.1016%2FS0019-9958%2885%2980046-2).\n24.  [↑](#cite_ref-24) [GNU Diff utilities](https://www.gnu.org/software/diffutils/) [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20150316032418/http://www.gnu.org/software/diffutils/) 2015-03-16 at the [Wayback Machine](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wayback_Machine \"Wayback Machine\"). Made available by the [Free Software Foundation](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_Software_Foundation \"Free Software Foundation\"). Free Documentation. Free source code.\n25.  [↑](#cite_ref-25) [\"merge (GNU RCS 5.10.0)\"](https://www.gnu.org/software/rcs/manual/html_node/merge.html). *gnu.org*. [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20190918125803/http://www.gnu.org/software/rcs/manual/html_node/merge.html) from the original on 18 September 2019. Retrieved 22 January 2021.\n26.  [↑](#cite_ref-26) [Moolenaar, Bram](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bram_Moolenaar \"Bram Moolenaar\"). [\"Vim documentation: diff\"](https://vimhelp.org/diff.txt.html#vimdiff). *vimdoc.sourceforge.net*. [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20200216203940/https://vimhelp.org/diff.txt.html#vimdiff) from the original on 16 February 2020. Retrieved 1 May 2020. The easiest way to start editing in diff mode is with the \"vimdiff\" command. This starts Vim as usual and also sets up for viewing the differences between the arguments. `vimdiff file1 file2 [file3] [file4] [...file8]` This is equivalent to: `vim -d file1 file2 [file3] [file4] [...file8]`\n27.  [1](#cite_ref-brabandt2018_27-0) [2](#cite_ref-brabandt2018_27-1) Brabandt, Christian (1 December 2018). [\"The power of diff\"](https://vimways.org/2018/the-power-of-diff/). *Vimways*. [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20181202020105/https://vimways.org/2018/the-power-of-diff/) from the original on 2 December 2018. Retrieved 1 May 2020.\n28.  [↑](#cite_ref-28) [\"gnu.org\"](https://gnu.org/s/wdiff/). *gnu.org*. [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20200811124535/https://gnu.org/s/wdiff/) from the original on 2020-08-11. Retrieved 2020-09-12.\n29.  [↑](#cite_ref-29) [\"colordiff\"](https://www.colordiff.org/). *www.colordiff.org*. [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20180614121429/https://www.colordiff.org/) from the original on 2018-06-14. Retrieved 2018-06-14.\n\n...33676 bytes truncated...\n\nThe tool call succeeded but the output was truncated. Full output saved to: /Users/michelkerkmeester/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_f5b5d49f7001jfLK611xC3Emt6\nUse the Task tool to have explore agent process this file with Grep and Read (with offset/limit). Do NOT read the full file yourself - delegate to save context.","metadata":{"truncated":true,"outputPath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_f5b5d49f7001jfLK611xC3Emt6"},"title":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diff (text/html; charset=UTF-8)","time":{"start":1783944268177,"end":1783944268285}},"id":"prt_f5b5d4821001CzcYFxWPr7QLxL","sessionID":"ses_0a4a439a7ffeIer0f3SFvzBG1A","messageID":"msg_f5b5d2555001lMmGGlPWRqRAD4"}}
